data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.4+ supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — compile-time type safety, no casting
- Array literals `["a", true]` → tuple literals `("a", true)`

This gives you refactor-friendly, type-checked test data. If you swap parameter types or add one, the compiler catches it immediately instead of failing at runtime.

Requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`MSTest.TestFramework` / `MSTest.Sdk`).
